So you have to do this and change a BIOS setting that's (usually) not in the BIOS menu to stop it locking the processor's voltages and sealing the setting before the OS loads:
https://www.ozbargain.com.au/node/559551

Obviously that guide's for Dell, but the general process is the same:
- extract BIOS update package that corresponds to the BIOS you have
- decompile
- find setting that's like "overclocking lock", "cfg lock", whatever, and make a note of its address and value
- boot to an EFI shell
- use ru.efi or grub.efi to change the variable by its hexadecimal address
- reboot, and throttlestop will work (but you will be vulnerable to processes escalating root privileges to "permanently install malware in BIOS" privileges*).

* which I don't think anyone should care about, but am mentioning for completeness.
